<TITLE> PSC asks CA to punish attackers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 4, (bdnews24.com)  The Public Service Commission chief on Thursday asked the chief adviser to punish the perpetrators who vandalised the Public Services Commission on Tuesday. PSC chairman Sa'adat Hossain and other members met with chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed at his office, presented a six-point proposal. They asked for personal security guards, even for sometime, for the PSC secretary and members. Candidates of the 27th BCS who were successful in the first and failed in the second exams, besieged and vandalised the PSC office in Dhaka. The PSC members termed the incident 'an act of terror'. After the incident, assistant secretary of PSC Ashraful Islam lodged a case at the Kafrul Police Station. Seventeen demonstrators had been arrested but they secured bail on Wednesday. The first result of the 27th BCS was cancelled amid allegations of political influence, corruption and irregularity and, later, new results were declared on Sept. 23, after another session of viva exams. As many as 3239 persons were appointed to different cadres but the selected candidates of the previous exam launched hunger strikes, rallies and other programmes in protest at the new appointment. They observed a fast-until-death hunger strike at the Central Shaheed Minar on Nov. 1 but broke the fasting on assurance by the education adviser that a 'logical solution' would be made. b
